description:
src/lib.rs:155-178 in get() — the function inline-handles 404 (NotFound), 401/403 (Backend with auth message), and falls through to map_http_status for everything else. src/lib.rs:236-240 in put() — only calls map_http_status, missing the auth/notfound differentiation entirely.

Idiomatic Rust pattern: have map_http_status own the full mapping. It already takes a status and a detail; it can produce SecretError::NotFound for 404 and the auth-aware message for 401/403, and the call sites become a uniform two-liner:

    if !status.is_success() {
        let detail = resp.text().await.unwrap_or_default();
        return Err(map_http_status(status, &detail));
    }

This addresses #5 (put missing auth message), #11 (readability), and #1 idiom (call-site duplication). The cost: map_http_status grows from ~12 lines to ~25, but those 25 lines live in one place, are unit-testable in isolation, and the get/put bodies shrink correspondingly.

Why it matters: any future status-code mapping change has to be applied in one place, not two. Right now any new branch (e.g. 409 Conflict for write contention) requires editing both get and put or risks divergence.
